'''Banca Adriatica S.p.A.''' trading as '''UBI Banca Adriatica''' and formerly known as '''Nuova Banca delle Marche S.p.A.''' was an Italian bank based in [[Jesi]], Marche region. It has operations in several regions in central Italy, but concentrated in Marche region, which 73% of the branches were located in that region as of 2016. The bank was formed on 22 November 2015 by the spin off of the good assets of the original '''Banca delle Marche S.p.A.'''.

Banca delle Marche was formed in 1994 by the merger of the [[savings bank]]s of Marche region. The bank faced capital shortfall and was nationalized by Italian National Resolution Fund in 2015 as Nuova Banca delle Marche,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2015/12/16/economia/quattro-banche-fallite-ecco-tutti-i-perch-JWSrQo73eOk0lqcSAL2fhK/pagina.html|title=Quattro banche fallite: ecco tutti i perché|date=16 December 2015|access-date=22 April 2018|work=La Stampa|language=Italian}}</ref> with toxic assets of the bank was spin off from the new [[legal person]]. The bank was bought by [[UBI Banca]] on 18 January 2017 for a nominal fee, renaming to Banca Adriatica. In the same year it was merged into UBI Banca.

==Predecessors==
The history of the bank could be traded back to some savings banks in Marche region in the town of [[Cassa di Risparmio di Jesi|Jesi]] (found 1844), in the Province of Macerata (found in 1929 by a merger of savings banks of [old] C.R. Macerata (found 1846), C.R. Camerino (found 1844), C.R. Recanati (found 1867) and C.R. Tolentino (found 1873)<ref>{{cite book|url=http://fondazionemacerata.it/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Statuto-2016.pdf|title=Statuto|date=2016|publisher=Fondazione Cassa di Risparmio della Provincia di Macerata|language=Italian|chapter= Art. 1 - (Costituzione e stemma) }}</ref>) and in the town of Pesaro (found in 1841).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fondazionecrpesaro.it/fondazione/?page_id=182|title=Cenni Storici|date=2014|orig-year=circa|accessdate=13 August 2018|publisher=Fondazione Cassa di Risparmio di Pesaro|language=Italian}}</ref>

==History==
'''Banca delle Marche''' was founded in 1994 by the merging of two banks: Cassa di Risparmio della Provincia di Macerata (C.R. Macerata) and Cassa di Risparmio di Pesaro (C.R. Pesaro); [[Cassa di Risparmio di Jesi]] (C.R. Jesi) joined in 1995. In 1990s [[Cassa di Risparmio delle Provincie Lombarde]] (Cariplo) was a minority shareholders of the bank for 5.13% (as in 1996),<ref>{{cite book|title=Cassa di Risparmio delle Provincie Lombarde S.p.A. bilancio al 1996-12-31|publisher=Italian [[Camera di Commercio, Industria, Agricoltura e Artigianato|C.C.I.A.A.]]|date=1997}}</ref> which Cariplo was a minority shareholder of CR Jesi in 1992;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzettaufficiale.it/eli/id/1992/04/17/092A1759/sg|title=Approvazione del progetto di ristrutturazione presentato dalla Cassa di risparmio di Jesi|date=17 April 1992|access-date=10 March 2016|newspaper=[[Gazzetta Ufficiale]]|language=Italian}}</ref> Cariplo's stake was diluted to 4.60% in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.group.intesasanpaolo.com/scriptIsir0/si09/contentData/view/Bilancial31dicembre2001.pdf?id=CNT-04-0000000026FF8&ct=application/pdf|title=2001 Bilancio|date=2 April 2002|access-date=10 March 2016|publisher=Banca Intesa|language=Italian}}</ref> then the stake was sold by [[Banca Intesa]], the successor of Cariplo to Banca delle Marche as treasury shares in 2002, for €45&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.group.intesasanpaolo.com/scriptIsir0/si09/contentData/view/1062669917832_bilancio2002.pdf?id=CNT-04-0000000027089&ct=application/pdf|title=2002 Bilancio|trans-title=2002 Annual Report|date=22 April 2003|access-date=10 March 2016|publisher=Banca Intesa|language=Italian}}</ref>

In 1997 Banca delle Marche acquired a controlling interest in [[Cassa di Risparmio di Loreto]] and Mediocredito Fondiario Centroitalia (Banca Marche owned 41.18% shares before the deal), the ''pro forma'' market share of the group in the loan of Marche region, was 26.7% (based on 1996 data), while before the acquisition, the bank already had a market monopoly of 53.6% in the deposits of the Province of Macerata (''pro forma'' 55.0% after the acquisition), comparing to [[Banca Popolare di Ancona]] (14%), [[Banca di Roma]] (6.38%) and [[Banca Nazionale del Lavoro]] (5.60%). The ''pro forma'' market share of the deposits in the Province of Ancona was 32.3%, which ahead Banca Popolare di Ancona (13.03%), [[Unicredito]] (11.04%) and Banca di Roma (9.78%).<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.agcm.it/concorrenza/concentrazioni/download/41256297003874BD/E333A8BAD7F585D7C12564660040D820.html?a=p4712.pdf|title=Provvedimento №4712 (C2704): Banca delle Marche / Cassa di Risparmio di Loreto / Mediocredito Fondiario Centro Italia|date=27 February 1997|access-date=10 March 2016|publisher=[[Italian Competition Authority]] (AGCM)|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/compiti/vigilanza/avvisi-pub/tutela-concorrenza/provvedimenti/provv20_18_03_97.pdf|title=Provvedimento №20: Banca delle Marche / Cassa di Risparmio di Loreto / Mediocredito Fondiario Centro Italia|date=18 March 1997|access-date=10 March 2016|publisher=Bank of Italy|language=Italian}}</ref>

On 1 July 2003 [[Sanpaolo IMI]] purchased 7% shares of the bank for €92.1 million. The banking foundations also had a [[put option]] to sell an additional 8% shares to Sanpaolo IMI.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.group.intesasanpaolo.com/scriptIsir0/si09/contentData/view/link?id=CNT-04-000000003EE38|title=Sanpaolo IMI acquires strategic stake in Banca delle Marche|date=1 July 2003|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Sanpaolo IMI}}</ref> However, the foundations did not excise the option. In 2007 the shares held by Sanpaolo IMI was transferred to [[Intesa Sanpaolo]] after a merger with Banca Intesa. Intesa Sanpaolo did not took part in the capital increase of Banca delle Marche in 2012, making the stake diluted.

===Insolvency===
On 24 October 2011, the board of directors proposed a capital increase of a minimum of €180,677,922.70 to a maximum of €212,562,262.00.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancamarche.it/aumento_capitale_sociale_2012_banca_delle_marche_spa|title=Aumento capitale sociale 2012 Banca delle Marche S.p.A.|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Banca delle Marche|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618080639/http://www.bancamarche.it/aumento_capitale_sociale_2012_banca_delle_marche_spa|archive-date=2016-06-18|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> After the capital increase (of €179,573,391<ref name=BancaMarche2012bilancio>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancamarche.it/download/Fascicolo%20individuale%2031_12_2012.pdf|title=2012 Bilancio Individuale|date=13 May 2013|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Banca delle Marche|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224220153/http://www.bancamarche.it/download/Fascicolo%20individuale%2031_12_2012.pdf|archive-date=2016-02-24|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>), as at 31 December 2012, the bank had a Tier 1 capital ratio of just 5.62% in consolidated balance sheets, with a shareholders' equity of €959.503 million.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.bancamarche.it/download/Fascicolo%20consolidato%2031_12_2012.pdf|title=2012 Bilancio Consolidato|trans-title=2012 Consolidated Financial Report|date=28 May 2013|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Banca delle Marche|language=Italian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919140117/http://www.bancamarche.it/download/Fascicolo%20consolidato%2031_12_2012.pdf|archivedate=19 September 2013}}</ref> According to a ranking by Ricerche e Studi, a subsidiary of [[Mediobanca]], Banca delle Marche was the 19th largest bank in Italy by total assets as at 31 December 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Le principali banche italiane|date=October 2013|work=Le principali società italiane|url=http://www.archiviostoricomediobanca.it/documenti/Le_Principali_Societa_Italiane_2013.pdf|issue=2013|accessdate=13 August 2018|issn=1721-274X|pages=292–293|publisher=Mediobanca|publication-place=Milan|language=Italian}}</ref>

On 15 October 2013 it was under special administration (A.S.) by a decree of [[Ministry of Economy and Finance (Italy)|the Ministry of Economy and Finance]], after a temporary administration by the [[Banca d'Italia|Bank of Italy]] in August.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/08/30/us-bancamarche-idUSBRE97T0TT20130830|title=Italy's Banca Marche put under special administration|date=30 August 2013|accessdate=10 April 2015|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/pubblicazioni/bollettino-vigilanza/2013-10/XII_BANCA_DELLE_MARCHE_221013_10_13.pdf|title=Banca delle Marche|date=October 2013|access-date=6 March 2016|work=Bollettino di Vigilanza|issue=10|publisher=Bank of Italy|language=Italian}}</ref> On 4 August 2014 [[Credito Fondiario (Fonspa)|Credito Fondiario]] credited Banca delle Marche for €1.8&nbsp;[[billion (short scale)|billion]],<ref name=FonspaMay2015/> which Credito Fondiario also planned to subscribe the new shares of Banca Marche, partnering with Italian [[deposit insurance]] fund the [[Fondo Interbancario di Tutela dei Depositi]] (FITD).<ref name=FITD2014bilancio/> The plan was approved by the Bank of Italy on 3 December 2014.<ref name=FITD2014bilancio>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitd.it/Pubblicazioni/Download/104|title=2014 Annual Report|date=27 February 2015|access-date=19 April 2016|publisher=Fondo Interbancario di Tutela dei Depositi}}</ref> However, the plan was scrapped due to [[European Commission]]'s investigation on state aid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/media/approfondimenti/2016/crisi-banca-marche/index.html?com.dotmarketing.htmlpage.language=102|title=La crisi di Banca delle Marche|access-date=19 April 2016|publisher=Bank of Italy|language=Italian}}</ref> After Banca Marche failed to repay the loan, Credito Fondiario sold the collaterals in May–June 2015,<ref name=FonspaMay2015>{{cite press release|url=http://m.bancamarche.it/ComunicatoStampa.aspx?id=328|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506164557/http://m.bancamarche.it/ComunicatoStampa.aspx?id=328|dead-url=yes|archive-date=6 May 2016|title=Press Release|date=20 May 2015|access-date=19 April 2016|publisher=Banca delle Marche}}</ref> which fully reimbursed the loan, with an excess amount was return to Banca Marche in June.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://m.bancamarche.it/ComunicatoStampa.aspx?id=332|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506184319/http://m.bancamarche.it/ComunicatoStampa.aspx?id=332|dead-url=yes|archive-date=6 May 2016|title=Press Release|date=25 June 2015|access-date=19 April 2016|publisher=Banca delle Marche}}</ref>

Another capital injection of more than €2&nbsp;billion to Banca Marche, Banca Etruria, Carife, and CariChieti by FITD was planned in late 2015, (€1.2 billion maximum for Banca Marche)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/marche/notizie/2015/10/27/fitd-2-mld-per-salvataggi-banche_99f298b0-699e-4459-b6d8-fced3b014f73.html|title=Fitd, 2 mld per salvataggi banche|trans-title=FITD, 2 billion to rescue banks|date=27 October 2015|access-date=9 April 2016|agency=ANSA|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitd.it/Pubblicazioni/Download/521|title=2015 Annual Report|date=29 March 2016|access-date=9 April 2016|publisher=Fondo Interbancario di Tutela dei Depositi}}</ref> subject to the permission from the Bank of Italy and [[European Central Bank]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.fitd.it/Comunicazioni/Download/4|title=Comunicato Stampa|date=8 October 2015|access-date=19 April 2016|publisher=Fondo Interbancario di Tutela dei Depositi|language=Italian}}</ref>

Eventually they were bail-out by [Italian] National Resolution Fund ({{lang-it|Fondo Nazionale di Risoluzione}}) on 22 November instead, for about €3.7 billion in total (€840 million for purchasing new shares of Banca Marche and an additional €1.206 billion to cover the previous loss of Banca Marche).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/pubblicazioni/rendiconto-fondo-nazionale-risoluzione/2016-rendiconto-fondo-nazionale-risoluzione/Regolamento_Fondo_Nazionale_Risoluzione_en.pdf.pdf?language_id=1|title=2015 Annual Report|chapter=Notes to the items of the balance sheet|pages=16–18|date=28 April 2016|access-date=13 August 2018|department=The National Resolution Fund|publisher=Bank of Italy}}</ref><ref name=bankofitaly>{{cite web|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/media/approfondimenti/2015/info-soluzione-crisi/index.html?com.dotmarketing.htmlpage.language=1|title=Information on resolution of Banca Marche, Banca Popolare dell'Etruria e del Lazio, Carichieti, and Cassa di Risparmio di Ferrara crises|date=22 November 2015|access-date=8 March 2016|publisher=Banca d'Italia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancamarche.it/download/Consolidato-31-12-2015_%20del%2022%20luglio%202016%20-%20A.pdf|title=Bilancio Consolidato 31 dicembre 2015|date=22 July 2016|access-date=23 September 2016|publisher=Nuova Banca delle Marche|language=Italian}}</ref>{{rp|9}} The rescue of the four banks were in line with EU [[Bank Recovery and Resolution Directive]], which was in force in Italy in late 2015. The Bank of Italy was the assigned "national resolution authority" of this [[Single Resolution Mechanism|mechanism]].<ref name=EC>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-6139_en.htm?locale=EN|title=State aid: Commission approves resolution plans for four small Italian banks Banca Marche, Banca Etruria, Carife and Carichieti|date=22 November 2015|access-date=9 March 2016|publisher=European Commission}}</ref> As the plans were following the directive, they were approved by the [[European Commission]].<ref name=EC/> Banca Marche assets and liabilities would split into good and bad bank, while the old bank would be liquidated,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzettaufficiale.it/eli/id/2016/03/05/16A01815/sg|title=Avvio della risoluzione di Banca delle Marche S.p.A., in Ancona, in amministrazione straordinaria|date=5 March 2016|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Italian Republic Official Gazette|language=Italian}}</ref> which the shareholders and [[subordinated debt|subordinated bond holders]] would receive nothing due to bail-in.<ref name=bankofitaly/> Among the former shareholders of the bank, as at 31 December 2015 Fondazione Carima had a net assets of €74,227,538, decreased from €154,175,111 year-to-year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fondazionemacerata.it/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/bilancio-esercizio-2015.pdf|title=2015 Bilancio dell'esercizio|date=12 May 2016|access-date=26 June 2016|publisher=Fondazione Cassa di Risparmio della Provincia di Macerata|language=Italian}}</ref> while Fondazione CR Pesaro had a net assets of €65,594,243, decreased from €169,830,262 year-to-year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fondazionecrpesaro.it/bilanci/bilcons2015.pdf|title=2015 Bilancio|date=29 April 2016|access-date=26 June 2016|publisher=Fondazione Cassa di Risparmio di Pesaro|language=Italian}}</ref> Fondazione CR Jesi suffered the most, which decreased from €76,388,622 to €10,989,510 year-to-year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fondazionecrj.it/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/BILANCIO-ODI-al-31-12-15.pdf|title=2015 Bilancio|date=16 June 2016|access-date=26 June 2016|publisher=Fondazione Cassa di Risparmio di Jesi|language=Italian}}</ref> all majority due to the write-down of the stake of old Banca delle Marche.

On 3 May 2016, Decree-Law No.59/2016 was announced, which the retail investors of the bond of the 4 banks would be refunded (up to €100,000, same as [[deposit insurance]]) if they purchased the bond on or before 12 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzettaufficiale.it/eli/id/2016/05/03/16G00076/sg|title=Decreto-legge 3 maggio 2016, №59|date=3 May 2016|access-date=21 July 2016|newspaper=[[Gazzetta Ufficiale]]|language=Italian}}</ref> The decree-law was a response to the criticism of the bail-in of all junior investors of the bank, which Italian bank often sold risky bond of themselves to their depositors. The refund scheme: ''Fondo di solidarietà'', would be managed by FITD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fitd.it/Home/FDS_normativa|title=Accesso al Fondo di Solidarietà|access-date=21 July 2016|publisher=FITD|language=Italian}}</ref>

===Nuova Banca Marche / Banca Adriatica===

On 22 November 2015 the bank was split into a bad and good bank, which the good bank was called ''' Nuova Banca delle Marche'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/media/notizia/soluzione-della-crisi-di-quattro-banche-in-amministrazione-straordinaria|title=Soluzione della crisi di quattro banche in amministrazione straordinaria|date=22 November 2015|access-date=13 February 2016|publisher=Bank of Italy|language=Italian}}</ref> The new bank had a provisional share capital of €1.041 billion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancamarche.it/download/Statuto.pdf|title=Statuto|trans-title=Articles of association|date=24 November 2015|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Nuova Banca delle Marche|language=Italian}}</ref> and an estimated Tier 1 capital ratio of 9%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancamarche.it/chi_siamo|title= Chi siamo|trans-title=About us|access-date=6 March 2016|publisher=Nuova Banca delle Marche|language=Italian}}</ref> While the bad debts were transferred to a single "bad bank" [[REV - Gestione Crediti]], which was shared with [[Cassa di Risparmio della Provincia di Chieti|Carichieti]], [[Cassa di Risparmio di Ferrara|Carife]] and [[Banca Popolare dell'Etruria e del Lazio|Banca Etruria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bancaditalia.it/compiti/risoluzione-gestione-crisi/provvedimenti-crisi/2015/provv-rilevanti/banca-marche/Banca_Marche_cessione_sofferenze_a_REV.pdf|title=Nuova Banca delle Marche S.p.A.. Cessione dei crediti in sofferenza a REV - Gestione Crediti S.p.A., ai sensi del D.Lgs. 180/2015.|date=29 January 2016|access-date=8 March 2016|publisher=Banca d'Italia|language=Italian}}</ref> The transfer of the bad debt was completed in early 2016.

In March 2016 a plan to absorb Medioleasing into Nuova Banca delle Marche was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancaditalia.it/compiti/risoluzione-gestione-crisi/provvedimenti-crisi/2016/provv-rilevanti/banca-marche/Banca_Marche_modifica_piano_di_risoluzione.pdf|title=Banca delle Marche S.p.A.. Modifica del programma di risoluzione, ai sensi del D.Lgs.180/2015 e decorrenza degli effetti.|date=11 March 2016|access-date=27 April 2016|publisher=Banca d'Italia|language=Italian}}</ref> On 1 August it became effective.<ref>http://www.bancamarche.it/medioleasing</ref> Focus Gestioni SGR, the asset management subsidiary of the bank, was also entered voluntary liquidation.

On 12 January 2017, [[UBI Banca]] made a binding bid of a nominal €1 for Nuova Banca Marche, Nuova CariChieti and Nuova Banca Etruria. The banking group also requested conditions that the balance sheets of the three banks would be cleaned up before the completion of the deal (which was done by selling NPLs to [[Atlante (private equity fund)|Atlante II]] and [[Credito Fondiario (Fonspa)|Credito Fondiario]]) as well as recapitalized for another €713&nbsp;million (was estimated €450&nbsp;million), by the National Resolution Fund. On 18 January the bid was accepted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancaditalia.it/media/comunicati/documenti/2017-01/cs_good_bank_eng.pdf?language_id=1|title=Sale of good banks to UBI|date=18 January 2017|access-date=19 January 2017|publisher=Bank of Italy}}</ref> On 10 May, the transaction was completed, which Nuova Banca Marche was renamed to '''Banca Adriatica'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ubibanca.it/contenuti/file/Closing,%20names%20and%20appointments_10052017.pdf|title=Closing of the deal to purchase the three Bridge Banks, new names and Senior Management appointments|date=10 May 2017|access-date=14 May 2017|publisher=UBI Banca}}</ref> On the same day, a plan to merge the 3 banks into UBI Banca was also announced.

On 23 October 2017, the merger was completed.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.ubibanca.it/contenuti/file/UBI%20Banca%20-%20Merger%20Banca%20Adriatica%20and%20CARILO%20into%20UBI%20Banca%20-%2017102017.pdf|title=Merger by incorporation of Banca Adriatica S.p.A. and Carilo – Cassa di Risparmio di Loreto S.p.A. into UBI Banca S.p.A.|date=17 October 2017|access-date=14 November 2017|publisher=UBI Banca}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.ubibanca.it/contenuti/file/COMUNICATO%2023%20ottobre%2020176.pdf|title=[no title]|date=23 October 2017|access-date=14 November 2017|publisher=UBI Banca}}</ref>

